{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487175"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:59:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"270"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/270"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.21,0.11,0.65,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/270"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42045"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44329"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a generalised pruritic rash, worse over his back and arms. The rash began three days after commencing cephalexin for treatment of a urinary tract infection which was sensitive only to this medication. He has tolerated amoxicillin in the past. He has no known drug allergies. His medical history is unremarkable. He does not take any regular medications. He is usually in good health, but since the rash started he has been feeling very tired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His temperature is 37.8\u00b0C, pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min and SpO2 99% on room air. His mucous membranes are dry, but intact. There is a crusty lesion on his left oral commissure, which he states has been present for a week. His chest is clear on auscultation. There are multiple scattered target-shaped lesions and erythematous round papules over his extensor surfaces, posterior trunk, palms and soles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute dermatitis","Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms","Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Erythema multiforme","Bullous pemphigoid"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with characteristic target-shaped lesions on the extensor surfaces, posterior trunk, palms, and soles, which is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is a mucocutaneous hypersensitivity reaction most commonly triggered by herpes simplex virus infection (mainly HSV-1), as suggested by the crusty lesion on the oral commissure (likely a cold sore). The use of cephalexin may have acted as a co-trigger or exacerbating factor. Erythema multiforme is typically self-limiting and resolves within two weeks, although recurrence occurs in approximately 5% of patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with erythematous, pruritic, and sometimes vesicular lesions, but does not characteristically produce the target-shaped lesions seen in this patient. Dermatitis is usually more diffuse and lacks the distinctive morphology described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms\u003C/strong\u003E (DRESS) is a severe, potentially life-threatening drug reaction that typically presents 2-6 weeks after initiating the causative medication, not within three days as in this case. DRESS syndrome is characterized by extensive skin eruption, fever, lymphadenopathy, hematologic abnormalities (particularly eosinophilia), and internal organ involvement, particularly the liver and kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (SJS) is a severe mucocutaneous reaction, usually drug-induced, characterised by widespread epidermal detachment and severe mucosal involvement. While atypical target lesions may appear in SJS, they tend to be macular rather than papular. SJS typically involves significant mucosal erosions and blistering, which are not described in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBullous pemphigoid\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune blistering disorder that typically affects older adults. It presents with tense bullae on an erythematous base, often in flexural areas, and is not characterised by target lesions. The onset is usually gradual rather than acute, and it is not typically associated with preceding infections or medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Target-shaped lesions are characteristic of erythema multiforme, which is commonly triggered by herpes simplex virus infection.","Erythema multiforme typically presents with target lesions on extensor surfaces, palms, and soles.","Erythema multiforme is usually self-limiting and resolves within two weeks, though recurrence is possible in about 5% of cases."],"references":["Lerch M, Mainetti C, Beretta-Piccoli BT, et al. Current Perspectives on Erythema Multiforme. Clin Rev All Immunol. 2018; 54:177-84. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29352387/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"270"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T12:37:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T12:37:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"270"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90588"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/